  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He set judges in the land, in all the fenced cities of Judah; they, as larger cities, being centres of communication for their respective neighbourhoods, and so best suited to be the seats of judges. ועיר לעיר, in reference to every city, as the law (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 16:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") prescribed. He laid it upon the consciences of these judges to administer justice conscientiously. \"Not for men are ye to judge, but for Jahve;\" i.e., not on the appointment and according to the will of men, but in the name and according to the will of the Lord (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 16:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In the last clause of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 19:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jahve is to be supplied from the preceding context: \"and Jahve is with you in judgment,\" i.e., in giving your decisions (cf. the conclusion of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 19:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); whence this clause, of course, only serves to strengthen the foregoing, only contains the thoughts already expressed in the law, that judgment belongs to God (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 21:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). Therefore the fear of the Lord should keep the judges from unrighteousness, so that they should neither allow themselves to be influenced by respect of persons, nor to be bribed by gifts, against which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 16:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also warns. ועשׂוּ שׁמרוּ is rightly paraphrased by the Vulgate, cum diligentia cuncta facite. The clause, \"With God there is no respect of persons,\" etc., recalls ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 10:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
